        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>July 16— 1878.</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>It is very kind of you to take so much trouble; but I beg you not to take any more, as I do not think it likely that there will be a new edition of my Forms of Flowers, &amp; unless there be one, I shall not be able to use all the information which you have been so good as to send me.—<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
                    <p>The <hi rend="underline">Stachys</hi> seems a very fine case of what I have called gyno-diœciousness.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>Your activity &amp; powers of observation seem very great.—</p>
<p>Dear Sir | Yours faithfully | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
             
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Whitelegge had been sending examples of gynodioecious plants; he later published his observations in <hi rend="italic">Nature</hi>, 3 October 1878, p. 588. This note was cited by CD when a second edition of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2613.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Forms of flowers</hi></ref> was published in 1880 (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_9500.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Forms of flowers</hi> 2d ed.</ref>, p. xvii).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11609.xml">letter from Thomas Whitelegge, 15 July 1878</ref>.</note>
        </div>   
       
